## Code Example
```java
// Kafka Streams topology for 5-minute rolling sums with late data handling
KStream<String, Long> events = builder.stream("user-events");

KTable<Windowed<String>, Long> sums = events
    .groupByKey()
    .windowedBy(
        TimeWindows.ofSizeAndGrace(Duration.ofMinutes(5), Duration.ofMinutes(2))
    )
    .sum();

sums.toStream()
    .mapValues((key, value) -> {
        String userId = key.key();
        long timestamp = key.window().start();
        return new KeyValue<>(userId + "|" + timestamp, value);
    })
    .to("aggregated-sums", Produced.with(Serdes.String(), Serdes.Long()));

// Late data compensation: emit tombstone then corrected value
sums.toStream()
    .foreach((windowedKey, sum) -> {
        String userId = windowedKey.key();
        long windowStart = windowedKey.window().start();
        redisTimeSeries.add(windowStart, sum, RetentionPolicy.MINUTES_30);
        // Compensating tombstone for late data corrections
        if (sum == 0) {
            redisTimeSeries.delete(windowStart);
        }
    });
```

## Windowing Strategy
- **Tumbling Windows**: Fixed, non-overlapping 5-minute windows align naturally with per-user aggregates
- **Watermark**: Marks the event time; events arriving after the watermark are considered late
- **Grace Period**: 2-minute grace allows late events within the watermark threshold to still be processed

## Backfill Strategy
1. Pause consuming new events from the Kafka topic
2. Reprocess historical events from the earliest offset using the same windowing logic
3. Overwrite RedisTimeSeries keys with corrected aggregates
4. Resume consuming from the checkpoint after backfill completes

